[normal]LPG 04[bold]Written submission from Peter Cumings (LPG 04)[bold]Improving Local Government Procuremen[bold]t: Implementing Public Services Social Value Act 2012[bold]In my work I support not for profit providers involved in public sector contracting; working daily on Local Authority tenders from across England. I am concerned that, overall, local authorities are being very slow in implementing PSSVA 2012. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Obviously it will take time to embed PSSVA practices into complex commissioning and procurement systems. However it is apparent that a significant number of local authorities have to date simply failed to respond at any level. Whilst my observations are anecdotal I am involved in local authority tendering on a daily basis. From my direct experience and from feedback gleaned from colleagues involved in local authority tendering support; I estimate social value questions appear in only half of ITTs and that and even where PSSVA compliant procurement exist they are  partial and stop gap. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I have worked on tenders in Scotland where the PSSVA equivalent, Community Benefits, has been up and running for some time. There are I feel lessons that could be learned from their approach to embedding Community Benefit clauses into public sector procurement. There are also some excellent examples of English local authorities that have progressed PSSVA on a strategic level.  
[normal]I would also comment that PSSVA thinking is yet to be fully integrated into national public sector procurement; NHS and in other areas such as Clinical Commissioning Groups.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Public sector bodies must pay attention to:
[normal]&#xa0;
